    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>I made a few renderers that worked, but only for objects, so I can\n  only conclude that renderers seem to not work for primitives.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>With IDEA 2016.3 it's finally possible to define custom Java Data Type Renderers for primitive types (including arrays).</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/idea/whatsnew/#v2016-3\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://www.jetbrains.com/idea/whatsnew/#v2016-3</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 8220865,
      "reputation" : 31,
      "user_id" : 6185439,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7dd9ee937367edd39780b8dd8e8cef8d?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "HajdaM",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6185439/hajdam"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1520704986,
    "last_edit_date" : 1520704986,
    "creation_date" : 1520634132,
    "answer_id" : 49203073,
    "question_id" : 21771305,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can also try <a href=\"https://plugins.jetbrains.com/plugin/9339\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">DeltaHex Editor plugin</a> for IntelliJ based IDEs which can show window with typical hex + text preview for byte array in debugger.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/AlPma.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/AlPma.png\" alt=\"DeltaHex Editor Plugin Debug Byte Array Image\"></a></p>\n\n<p>Plugin is available in Settings/Plugins/Browse repositories/Search for DeltaHex</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 223715,
      "reputation" : 12995,
      "user_id" : 483113,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 89,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5e6ce1def86e084cf06ac3a5a7e2d74f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "sjngm",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/483113/sjngm"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1762522551,
    "creation_date" : 1762522551,
    "answer_id" : 79812395,
    "question_id" : 21771305,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This question is still valid after so many years... The hard part is to understand what Java syntax those expressions actually support. They clearly <strong>must not</strong> contain lambdas, but allow actual Java, i.e. not just one-liners. Furthermore, the result of the expression doesn't need to have as many elements as the array.</p>\n<p>For <code>byte</code>-arrays I dislike that they are always rendered in the range -128 to 127. Therefore, here is the expression for type <code>byte[]</code> that renders a byte as signed, unsigned and hex:</p>\n<pre><code>String[] str = new String[this.length];\nfor (int i = 0; i &lt; str.length; i++) {\n  str[i] = &quot;%1$4s | %2$3d | 0x%1$02X&quot;.formatted(this[i], this[i] &amp; 0xFF);\n}\nreturn str;\n</code></pre>\n<p><em>It's supposed to look like a table and it would if the display would use a monospace font.</em></p>\n<p>You need to put the expression into the &quot;When expanding a node | Use following expression&quot;-field. For &quot;When rendering a node&quot; I still use the default renderer.</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://i.sstatic.net/rEAf21Rk.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/rEAf21Rk.png\" alt=\"Sample output\" /></a></p>\n"
  } ],
